Use reference on your foreach like so **&amp;$key** to save your modification :

PHP make a copy of the variable in the foreach, so your **$key** is not actually the same as the one from your previous array.

From @[Dharman][1] :

&gt; &amp; passes a value of the array as a reference and does not create a new
&gt; instance of the variable.

So just do :


    $arr = array(array(&quot;blue&quot;),array(&quot;green&quot;));
    
    foreach ($arr as &amp;$value)
    {
        $value[]=&#39;yellow&#39;;
        print_r($value);
    }
    foreach ($arr as $value)
    {
        print_r($value);
    }


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15024616/php-foreach-change-original-array-values

Here is [foreach][1] no key approach 

    $arr = [[&quot;blue&quot;], [&quot;green&quot;]];
    foreach ($arr as &amp;$value)
           $value[]=&#39;yellow&#39;;        
    print_r($arr);
Here is [foreach][1] with key approach

    $arr = [[&quot;blue&quot;], [&quot;green&quot;]];
    foreach ($arr as $key=&gt;$value)
           $arr[$key][]=&#39;yellow&#39;;        
    print_r($arr);

Here is another approach using [array_walk][2]

    $arr = [[&quot;blue&quot;], [&quot;green&quot;]];
    array_walk($arr, function(&amp;$item) {
        $item[] = &quot;yellow&quot;;
    });
    print_r($arr);
Here is the same thing with [array_map][3]

    $arr = [[&quot;blue&quot;], [&quot;green&quot;]];
    $arr = array_map(function($item) {
        $item[] = &quot;yellow&quot;;
        return $item;
    }, $arr);
    print_r($arr);

Output for all examples

    Array
    (
        [0] =&gt; Array
            (
                [0] =&gt; blue
                [1] =&gt; yellow
            )
    
        [1] =&gt; Array
            (
                [0] =&gt; green
                [1] =&gt; yellow
            )
    
    )
And finally some performance tests [speed][4] and [memory_usage][5]


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/control-structures.foreach.php
  [2]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-walk.php
  [3]: http://docs.php.net/manual/da/function.array-map.php
  [4]: http://sandbox.onlinephpfunctions.com/code/f71c9f79b225a454e4fc36781e4d071bda9f154c
  [5]: http://sandbox.onlinephpfunctions.com/code/14a5f12296c95a3520de5e96eaa15bbb82e31779

You can also use array_map for this. See the below code for example.

    $a = [[&quot;blue&quot;],[&quot;green&quot;]];
              
    $b = array_map(function($n) {
        $n[] = &quot;Yellow&quot;;
        return $n;
    }, $a);

    print_r($b);

Hope this helps.

